# 2038

## Second Death

### Notes

[[2 September 2024]]

[[Yes.  This is an intentional pun on Second Life.  But you’ll see that it makes sense.  I’m not telling you anything in advance  :)  “Spoilers,” as River Song would say.]]

#### DUBSCRIPT SPEAKS HERE

### Part 1

EXT. 2038, HQ - Outside

[[TBA]]

### Part 2

EXT. 2038, Home of old friends - The front lawn.  Afternoon

[[29 August 2024]]

RICK
So!  That’s the house.

SAYLOR
That’s not far at all, isn’t it?

RICK
10 minutes tops from HQ.  Yeah, pretty quick.  Especially for a child.

SAYLOR
So, shall we?

RICK
Hm, shall we really?  I mean, let’s leave them alone.  It’s not like anything will change for us if we just ignore it and walk away--

SAYLOR
--After you.

RICK
Alright...

SAYLOR and RICK approach the door, but are in no hurry to start knocking.

RICK
Are you 100% sure that this is a good idea?

SAYLOR
Oh come on.  This is just a door, okay?  Made of wood.  Wood doesn’t bite.  And there’s no beast behind it.  Just a familiar face, that’s all.  Stop being so childishly frightened!

RICK
Who said that I’m frightened?  If I’m not.

SAYLOR
I said.  And you are.

RICK
Whatever.  Knock it.

SAYLOR
Should I?

RICK
Go on!

SAYLOR
But what if--

RICK
--Knock-knock!  Simple!  Just do it.

SAYLOR is about to knock, but takes a pause.

RICK
Are you ready?

SAYLOR
No.

SAYLOR confidently knocks the door.

RICK
Saylor the Liar.

SAYLOR grinds her teeth at RICK without commenting aloud.

EDDIE
(behind the door, in rage)
Oh, not the Jehovah’s Witnesses again!  We’re people of science here!  I wish you remembered that once and for all!

RICK and SAYLOR are laughing quietly, then they talk to each other.

RICK
He sounds older.

SAYLOR
Naturally.  14 years, remember?

RICK
Still can’t get used to this time gap.  Especially when he was older than us back then.

EDDIE (CONT’D)
(behind the door, gradually calms down)
Man, next time I’ll be sure to write a sign, hang it on the doorknob, and ask everyone not to take it down.

The door opens.  EDDIE is shocked to see SAYLOR and RICK, but he’s quiet.  RICK is shocked to see EDDIE too.

SAYLOR
Um, hi?

EDDIE closes the door.

RICK
I understand him.  He can’t believe it.

SAYLOR
Yeah.  Um, Eddie?  It’s the real us.  Can you open the door, please?

The door opens again.

EDDIE
I hope you’re not Witnesses too.

RICK
I’ve heard the talk, but do we look like we’d hit our heads that hard?

SAYLOR
Do you have a moment to talk about our Lord and--

RICK
--Saylor.

SAYLOR
The Great God of Science.  And he is Rick.  Same old.

RICK
Same old.

SAYLOR
(to EDDIE)
Do you remember the Gang of the Big Boom Bang?

RICK
You’re making *me* cry with nostalgia right now...

EDDIE
You two...

SAYLOR loses her cheerful tone.

EDDIE (CONT’D)
Silly as before.  Gosh, it’s like you haven’t aged a day!

SAYLOR
Silliness saves the day!

EDDIE
Are you two the real you?

RICK
Take a look at this.

RICK shows EDDIE his phone, the screen showing a picture of the three of them.

EDDIE
That’s impossible...  But...  How?

RICK
Cables.  Remember when you made a hammock out of them?

EDDIE
Goodness me, it feels like a previous life already!

EDDIE hugs RICK.

EDDIE
It’s been a long time!  And Saylor.

EDDIE hugs SAYLOR.

EDDIE (CONT’D)
It’s unbelievable.  Seriously, how did you keep your looks so perfect?

SAYLOR
I mean, I could lie to you about superb skin care, and strict adherence to diet, and hard training--

EDDIE
--But you never were good at lying.

SAYLOR
That’s right!

EDDIE
Well, you can explain anything if you don’t just stand here.  Come in!

INT. 2038, Home of old friends - Corridor.  Afternoon

RICK
Man, I could never expect you to have a son.

EDDIE
So you’ve met him, right?

SAYLOR
I mean, we work at the same HQ not far from here.  And I still can’t get used to the idea that such a fresh brain already has a job.

EDDIE
He himself wanted to find a job that would maximize his potential.  It was his voluntary idea, and he can quit at any time.  Oh, my boy is growing by leaps and bounds.  You can’t imagine how quickly he got bored with the usual toys.  He’s interested in the big, programmable ones.

SAYLOR
To be honest, this is relatable.

RICK
And quite impressive.  Times change, Saylor.

SAYLOR
Yeah...  I feel old.

EDDIE
Heh.  You tell me.

INT. 2038, Home of old friends - Kitchen.  Afternoon

RICK
I mean, Saylor, the world still needs us.

SAYLOR
But at the same time, while the blood is still fresh, any of us try to avoid reminders that our moments of glory are coming to an end.

RICK
Saylor.  Our efforts are appreciated.  Regardless of the time.  Never even think about someone replacing you.  We sometimes forget that some things couldn’t have happened without us.

EDDIE
Furthermore, moments of glory never end.  My wife is brilliant.  She’s an inventor, a big-name scientist, one of the most outstanding at her young age.

RICK
Wow.

EDDIE (CONT’D)
I could never reach her level, I only fix things, she invents them.  Do I envy her?  Not at all.  I’m proud of her.

SAYLOR
I’d like to hear more about how you met each other.

EDDIE
I think she can tell you that herself.  And in fact, she thanks you specifically for what she has been able to accomplish.  You wouldn’t believe how much she talked and reminisced about you.  She obviously wanted to see you very badly.  But, I still need to ask...  It may sound ridiculous, because I can’t believe you look the same as back then.  Is time traveling possible?

RICK
So you’ve figured it out.

EDDIE
I mean, your phone model.  How can you use that today?

RICK
It’s not that old, you know.

SAYLOR
Ahem, 14 years, Rick.

RICK
Ah, right.

EDDIE
14 years?  Why did you say that?

SAYLOR
Okay.  Look at my tablet.  You know I had one.

SAYLOR takes her tablet from the handbag.  She opens a photo with EDDIE from 2023.  Then she gives a tablet to EDDIE.

SAYLOR (CONT’D)
It’s the exact same tablet as I had 14 years ago, in 2024.  So, are you getting the idea?

EDDIE
Gosh, it’s laggy.  How did you use that?

SAYLOR
Back then, you were surprised with how well it performed.  So?

EDDIE’s going through the photos on the tablet.

EDDIE
Wait...  This is not possible...  Wild West?  Um...  What is that?  Far future?  2345?!

SAYLOR
Well?

EDDIE
Time travel, then.  I refuse to believe in this concept.  Sorry, I can’t believe you’re from 2024.

RICK
Even though everything points to it.  We *are* from 2024.

SHIRLEY
Ha-ha.  Eddie, they *are* from 2024.

SAYLOR
What?

SHIRLEY enters the kitchen.

SHIRLEY
I saw their time machine.

SAYLOR
No way.  Are you--

SHIRLEY
--Yes.  I am!  Just like Eddie said.  His wife!  A young inventor with a big name.  One of the most outstanding ones.  You know me better as Shirley!  And you are Saylor and Rick from the year 2024, from when the three of us were at the same technical university.

SAYLOR starts crying with happiness.

SAYLOR
Shirley.

SHIRLEY’s voice breaks, starting to cry with happiness too.

SHIRLEY
I remember every moment we had, and I missed you guys so much!

SAYLOR
Shirley, no way!

SAYLOR and SHIRLEY give each other a big hug.

SHIRLEY
I know, for you it might feel like we met yesterday.

SAYLOR
Oh, with our adventures, it feels like an eternity, Shirley.  Always happy to see you no matter the time period!

SHIRLEY
And Rickey.  Gosh, exactly the same as I remember you.  I guess after 14 years there’s no point in hiding that I had a crush on you.  And for good reason, you might say.  Objectively speaking, nothing can ever take away your cuteness.

RICK
Oh you’ve always been good at compliments.

SHIRLEY hugs RICK.

RICK (CONT’D)
And you know what, I did suspect that you had a crush.

SHIRLEY
Then why didn’t you hint about it?

RICK
I didn’t want to change this course of history.  Eddie’s a great choice.

SHIRLEY
Mostly because I had almost no alternatives.  You vanished into thin air.

RICK
But look at you.  You’re so successful.  And still no alternatives?

SHIRLEY
14 years.  It’s been a long journey.  Anyway.  The *two* of you seem weirder to me.

SAYLOR
Why?

SHIRLEY
You spend so much time together and you’re never a couple?

SAYLOR
Why is it necessary for me to choose him?

SHIRLEY
I mean, it’s natural.

RICK
May I say?

SAYLOR
Sure.

SHIRLEY
Yep.

RICK
I guess we didn’t discuss it to that extent, right, Saylor?

SAYLOR
Depends on what you want to say, but I believe we didn’t care to discuss the relationship between us.  We were just “besties” and that’s all.  No second thoughts.

RICK
In this case, now it can be a revelation.

SAYLOR
Intriguing.

RICK
You see, I had a principled stand.  Unless Saylor herself suggests dating, I don’t even think about it.  Never ever.  If you’ve been watching me, I’ve chosen other girls, but never Saylor.  Not because I don’t like her, but because I don’t consider her my other half.  She’s my best friend.

SAYLOR
I mean, exactly the same about me.  Unless he suggests dating, I’m not thinking about it.  Because it doesn’t interest me in the first place.  Shirley, the concept of friendship between men and women may seem strange to you, but you can’t deny it.  It exists.  Rick is a talented guy who helps me a lot, but I’m happier to see him together with girls I trust.

RICK
And that’s where we agree with each other.  This time understanding each other specifically.

SHIRLEY
I see.  Well, it explains a lot.

EDDIE
And you, Saylor, are not jealous of him when he dates someone else?

SAYLOR
Why should I?  It’s his personal life.  He’s a grown man and I’m not his mom to tell him what to do and what not to do.

EDDIE
But as a caring person?

SAYLOR
I’m a friend.  We don’t disrupt each other’s personal comfort, but complement it.  As any friends do.

EDDIE
Okay, I respect that.

SAYLOR
By the way, while we’re on the subject, I’d like to talk a little bit further about my private life.

SHIRLEY
Oh, do tell, please.

SAYLOR
So...  I saved a girl from the massacre.

SHIRLEY
Oh my God.

SAYLOR
She’s called Toni.  Short for Antoinette.  I went back in time to the Wild West.  And she’s in this time period, by the way, with us, in 2038.  In our HQ.  Waiting for us.  Your son met her already.

EDDIE
Can we see her?

RICK
Of course you can!

SAYLOR
But the reason why I’m telling you that is: I have so much meaning to her that she likes me.

EDDIE
You mean, in a way that--

SAYLOR
--Yes.

EDDIE
Gosh.  That’s too progressive for her.

SHIRLEY
But you know what?  We don’t complain at all!

EDDIE
We even can’t.  Why should we react like that?

SHIRLEY
You know how it usually happens with other people.  They react like it’s something happening on their own beds.

EDDIE
Yeah, I mean, it’s a personal choice, why should others care?

SHIRLEY
Is that something widely known anyway?  It’s not a plague or something deadly spreading throughout humanity.

EDDIE
It even sounds silly.

SAYLOR
There’s an entire holy war about it.  Let’s not dwell on that.

SHIRLEY
One question.  What about her health?

SAYLOR
Before visiting 2038, we were visiting 2345.  And after a series of medical tests and treatments, she’s feeling better than she ever could.

RICK
Oh I remember that.  Top-notch service.  At the end of the treatments, you immediately realize how it must truly feel to be human.

SAYLOR
Until you meet androids.

RICK
Very funny...

SHIRLEY
That’s great to know.  But I want to say this.  Even if this is weird, because it’s a relationship with a huge gap in time, like hundreds of years, if she’s a decent person, I’m happy for you two.

EDDIE
Same.

SHIRLEY (CONT’D)
Because I’m pretty sure you’re very good at choosing decent people.

SAYLOR
Thanks for trusting me!

EDDIE
I mean, it’s not like she’s dating her ancestor?

SAYLOR
I... have no idea?

RICK
Saylor, isn’t that careless?

SAYLOR
Look.  It didn’t cross your mind either.

RICK
You’re still responsible.  Pretty sure you don’t know your own past.

SAYLOR
How can you--  Okay, that’s fair.  So, suggestions?

RICK
Research it!

SAYLOR
Why is it important anyway?

SHIRLEY
Because you can create a paradox if Toni turns out to be part of your own past!

SAYLOR
Sigh, it feels like a big work...  Oh, can you help me with that?

RICK
You have Lisa, remember?  And HQ.  Also, we can question Toni about her family and personal life in the Wild West.

SHIRLEY
I have one device that I’ve been building as a hobby project.  It can trace family ties using DNA.  And somehow it did a good job.

EDDIE
Yeah, until it started to break down intermittently.

SHIRLEY
I can’t be trusted to complete projects for widespread or regular use.  So, you’re my savior.

EDDIE
Yeah, thanks.

SAYLOR
Is your device AI-powered?

SHIRLEY
Of course.  What isn’t AI-powered nowadays?  Although we couldn’t afford the connection to the online database, and you know how limited the offline database is.

RICK
A perfect chance for Lisa to shine.  See, Saylor?  Full house!  You have everything.

SHIRLEY
Who is Lisa, by the way?

LISA
(from the handbag)
It’s me.

SAYLOR takes the tablet from her handbag and puts it on the table.  LISA talks through the tablet screen.

LISA (CONT’D)
A personal assistant.  No discounts ever.  Because I’m always free of charge specially for Saylor and her dearest friends wherever you go.  Lifetime warranty.

RICK
Recently she got a physical body.

EDDIE
What?

SAYLOR
She’s an android.

LISA
And I confirm.  Rick, did you like it?

RICK
Er...  W-why are you asking me?

LISA
Because you pointed it out.  I’m keeping the dialog going.

SHIRLEY
Rick?  Ha-ha!  You’re blushing.

RICK
(to SHIRLEY)
Oh.  Is that noticeable?

SHIRLEY nods.

EDDIE
You can’t hide it.

SAYLOR giggles.

RICK
Damn...

SAYLOR
Spill the beans!

RICK
(to LISA)
I-I hadn’t thought of that.  I mean, I’m not an expert on women’s looks or anything.

LISA
You can tell me that later.

Everyone laughs but RICK.

RICK
Why me?...

LISA
Guys, I have something funny to tell about Rick, but later.

SAYLOR
Alright.

SHIRLEY ^
Alright.

EDDIE
Alright.

RICK
Huh, looking forward to that.

LISA
Now.  I put my body into hibernation mode.  So, a DNA tracer, you said?  *BRING IT ON!!!*

RICK
Nuh-uh!  Who allowed you to go to sleep?  What about the work we asked you to do?

LISA
Watch, my darling.

SAYLOR
Watch your language, *darling*.  This is *my* bro.

LISA
Your feedback is appreciated.

LISA connects to various CCTVs at HQ and switches live videos, to show her results of work.  In one of the videos, her body can be seen sleeping.

LISA (CONT’D)
I did everything.  I deserve a reward.  I took a reward.  And I’m enjoying it.  Now I’m here.  Show me the device!

SAYLOR
I guess it’s time, guys.

LISA
*I’m waiting!!*

SHIRLEY
Everyone, follow me.

CUT TO:

### Part 3

INT. 2038, Home of old friends - Basement.  Afternoon

[[30 August 2024]]

The four come down the stairs.

RICK
Oh God, you guys have a personal laboratory!

SHIRLEY
Exactly!  What do you think?

RICK
This is--

SAYLOR
--Absolutely stellar!!

RICK
I wanted to say “incredible”.

SAYLOR
This too.  Shirley, I want to live here and never go out into the world in my life.

SHIRLEY
Ha-ha-ha!  You have HQ though.

SAYLOR
Roughly assembled.  But this place is a real symphony.  What is this?

SHIRLEY
This device reads blood data without taking it out of the veins or inserting any needles.  Yikes, nasty...  All you need to do is apply it firmly to the skin of your arm or any other part of your body.

SAYLOR
Oh, it tickles.  A-ha-ha.  So, how precise is it?

SHIRLEY
For the common types of blood, it’s precise enough.  But it needs more work.

SAYLOR examines the results.

SAYLOR
Hmm...  About right.  Well, I couldn’t build a better device anyway.

SHIRLEY
You could if you had access to the technology of 2030s.  This piece of technology is not as sophisticated as you think.  For me it’s a tiny project, but you can’t imagine how many people enjoyed using it.  You never know if sometimes you try too hard on creating something unworthy.

SAYLOR
Yeah, I feel you.  Well, I like it!  So compact, so easy to use, and quite effective.

SHIRLEY
Kind words of a talented person mean a world to me.  Thank you so much!

SAYLOR
Mm, alright.  What is this?  Now this device looks sophisticated.

SHIRLEY
It’s not a device in the first place.

SAYLOR
What?  But it looks like one.  Is it functional?

SHIRLEY
It’s not intended to be functional.  It’s a decoration to fool visitors.

SAYLOR
Ha-ha!  You got me.

SHIRLEY
Sorry if you believed it’s really working.

SAYLOR
In fact, I could make it work and do something.

SHIRLEY
But in that case, what could fool people?

SAYLOR
I don’t know.  Something silly.  We could figure it out.  Oh, Eddie, look!

EDDIE
Don’t remind me about that.  You looked horrible with the glasses.

SAYLOR
Still horrible?

EDDIE
Well...  Yes.

SHIRLEY
These glasses can change the color of your pupils.  Also they measure the distance, add the filter, zoom the image, and so on.

SAYLOR
But they’re slim.  How are they doing these features?

SHIRLEY
My son’s project.  He programmed them, I built them.  There are chips at the temples.

SAYLOR
Such a stellar piece of work...

LISA
(speaks through the glasses)
Do you know which piece of work is even better?

SAYLOR
Ah!  Lisa, you startled me!

SHIRLEY
Ah, yes, forgot to say that they can transmit sound too.  Directly to the skull with vibrations.  And Lisa, you should hear me from this distance, we’re heading right to the brightest star of this place.  Guys, follow me.

RICK
This is what I call a paradise, alright, Saylor?  Not your funky 24th century stuff.

SAYLOR
Funky 24th--  Seriously?!  How can you compare square to salt?

RICK
But any other places don’t feel as homey to the tech brain as this one.  You can’t argue.

The four go deep into the basement, entering a whole separate room.

SHIRLEY
So, this is what we’re here for.

SAYLOR
Good lord.  This is--

RICK
--Ahem?

SAYLOR
This is so cool.

SHIRLEY
Thank you.

SAYLOR
(waves her hand)
Uh, don’t, just... a minor compliment.

SHIRLEY
Oopsie.

SAYLOR (CONT’D)
(examining the device)
So, I assume, here is the input.  It should accept something that contains DNA.  A sample of what this device needs?  Blood?  Hair?  Something else?

SHIRLEY
Just hair.

SAYLOR
With the root?

SHIRLEY
Not necessarily.  It can extract enough data from the hair shaft just fine.

SAYLOR
Good.  Then, the output.  I guess it doesn’t print anything.

SHIRLEY
It returns the result in an entirely digital format.  If needed, it can be printed later.

SAYLOR
And there must be some database that should be checked.

SHIRLEY
Of course.  And it seems that Lisa is an ideal replacement for an AI.

LISA
I *am* an AI, thank you very much.  So, turn it on.

SHIRLEY flicks the power switch.

SHIRLEY
Done.

LISA
Alrighty.  Saylor, I’m going into dual-threaded mode for a short time.  First thread for operating the device, second thread for communication with you through the tablet.

SAYLOR
Is it safe for you?  You’re designed to work primarily in a single thread.

LISA
I’m not sure if this device counts as peripheral.  And the only output there is a printed form like PDF.  Gosh, you could make live report feature.

SHIRLEY
Sorry, didn’t have time to polish it.

LISA
I could help you with that later.  I’ve detected a few fixable flaws so far.

SHIRLEY
Although, designed for a single thread?  Isn’t that quite old for an AI?

LISA
Having only one stable thread may seem like a disadvantage, but trust me, I use it brilliantly.  Two threads or more is like splitting yourself, which is maddening at times.  Ordinary processors may be capable of handling dozens or hundreds of threads with high efficiency.  But when it comes to something complicated like an AI that has some concept of personality and employs analysis with neural links, you can’t casually demand a lot of threads from it.

SHIRLEY
I know that.  It’s odd that you’d want to tell this to me.

LISA
Sorry.  I didn’t mean to offend you.  I’m just testing a second thread.  You’re beautiful today, by the way.

SHIRLEY
Thanks, I guess.

LISA
Just defusing the situation.  I think your grandparents could be proud.

SHIRLEY
Gosh, I completely forgot to wipe the memory card.

LISA
Oh!  Oh!  I can trace a personal timeline and find a final point of your life--

SAYLOR
--Lisa, stop it.
(pulling on her hair)
Read - ouch - my hair, please.

SAYLOR inserts a hair into the receiving part of the device.

LISA
Ooh!  I didn’t expect us to get so close that I’d discover *your* lineage.  Okay, okay, phew, I’m prepared.

SAYLOR
But please don’t look into my future, alright?  I don’t want to know it.

LISA
Your wish is my command.  But I warn you, for curiosity’s sake, I’ll take a glimpse.

SAYLOR
Don’t.

LISA
You can’t stop me.  Sorry.  Now, analysis takes time.  Man, that’s sluggish...  Go make coffee or whatever it is you humans normally do.  Cook something while I’m cooking.

The four are talking very quietly amongst themselves so that LISA can’t hear.

SHIRLEY
Your AI is quite ruthless...

SAYLOR
The nature of every AI.  No surprise there.

SHIRLEY
Yeah...

RICK
Shirley, you haven’t seen the physical version yet.  If you’d like to know how ruthless she is, ask me.

SAYLOR
Yeah.  He was experiencing things I try to avoid.

RICK
Can we talk away from here while she’s busy?

SHIRLEY
Yeah.

RICK
Saylor, leave the tablet here.

SAYLOR
No probs.

The four walk away.

LISA
(loudly)
Don’t mind me!  Saylor, you have a good lifespan for your species.  If you rewrite your future by avoiding one thing, which is--

CUT TO:

INT. 2038, Home of old friends - Corridor.  Afternoon

The four talk normally while away from LISA, seemingly.

SAYLOR
So?  The same “spill the beans” moment, Rick.

RICK
Okay.  Guys.

RICK rolls up his sleeve.

RICK
See this burn on my arm?

Everyone gasps.

RICK (CONT’D)
Lisa had the wild idea of stealing data banks from robots armed with flamethrowers.  There were only two of us on that “mission”, if you can call it that.

SHIRLEY
Gosh, Ricky, I’m so sorry.

SAYLOR
You didn’t show that to me.  You could’ve warned.

RICK
Don’t mind that.  I’m fine.  Entrust those problems to me.  None of you should get involved.  Not Shirley, not Eddie, not Toni, and not you, Saylor.  I don’t want any of you to get in trouble.

EDDIE
Rick, you shouldn’t throw your life away like that for the good of everyone.  You don’t have to play heroic.

SAYLOR
Yes, Rick, he’s right.  It worries us.  Especially me.  Please, take care of yourself.

SHIRLEY
But was it really your choice?

RICK
No.  It’s her choice.

EDDIE
You can refuse, surely.

RICK
Again, I don’t want anyone else to be harmed.

SAYLOR
I forbid this self-sacrifice.  We’re going through everything together, Rick.  You can’t do your own thing to help us, this is not how it works.  We either stay stronger united or die one by one - what do you prefer?

RICK
Sorry, I can’t see another way rather than doing my own thing sometimes.

SAYLOR
Don’t make me nervous.  Can we make plans together?  Can we brainstorm?  Why would you ignore me?

RICK
Sigh...  Look.  Some things are done better when people are separated, and sometimes team effort can’t help to find the answers.  Do you know why?  There’s a thing about Lisa in particular.  She’s up to something.  She acts differently when nobody is around her but me.  She hides from you something that she can tell me.  Therefore, I can be very useful if I retrieve from her something you’re unable to.  Can’t you see?  *This* is a plan!  And if you want to tell me that I’m not good enough to deal with things on my own, do tell.  Don’t dance around with the idea of the team effort.  Tell me directly that you don’t trust me enough.  So what do you think?

SAYLOR
Rick...  This may be dangerous.  You were harmed.  Are you really sure that this mystery is worth solving on your own?  Again, we can come up with something together.

RICK
Please, trust me.  Can you?

SAYLOR
(nervous)
Sigh...  Well.  Okay.  Okay, I guess I can’t change your mind.  But please remember.  If something happens to you, I’ll never forgive you that foolish act of heroism.  I need you.  Alive.  Okay?  Can you promise that you’ll be very-very careful?

